SATIRE V.

On fortune-hunting. An imaginary dialogue between Ulysses and Tiresias, whose advice, we must suppose, represents the actual trickeries resorted to by the dependente of rich men and needy expectante of a legacy. The methods exposed are presente (v. 11‚) companionship (v. 17,) legal aid and advocacy (v. 27, sqq.) general suppleness and fiattery.

Their usual success is described; their occasional detection and rebuff is illustrated in the story os Nasica and Coranus (vv. 56-69.)
